When splitting the dataset in train/test-sets, users/books may be poorly represented in the resulting sets.

This is why, after performing a 75%-25% train/test split, I have computed the ratio of ratings for each book/user that have been selected in the training test and plotted them below.

The resulting distributions will be centered around 25% and should not contain too many extreme values (values close to 0% and 100%).

This is where we define and train our neural network.

The InputLayer will receive pairs of values as input (which represent the user/book IDs) and will send each to their coresponding embeddings via the Lambda layers. These IDs will be used by the embeddings to select a row from their weights and them forward in the network.

The Multiply layer is supposed to identify the features of the book that the user will find appealing and the subsequent Dropout layer is there to mimick lack of knowledge (which our network should be robust against). The user/book biases are concatenated to this output. The reason why they don't go through tha Multiply-Dropout phase is because they are supposed to represent inherent qualities such as a book's popularity or a user's degree of criticism.

The resulting values are fed to a feed-forward neural network with the task of regressing over the ratings.

In [136]:
import keras.backend as K
from keras.models import Model
from keras.layers import Dense, Embedding, Multiply, Input, Dropout, Lambda, Concatenate
from keras.utils.vis_utils import model_to_dot

def recommender(user_count, item_count, property_count):
    inp = Input(shape=(2, ), dtype='int32')
    
    u_select = Lambda(lambda x: x[:, 0] - 1, name='user_selector')(inp)
    u_emb = Embedding(user_count, property_count, name='users')(u_select)
    u_emb_bias = Embedding(user_count, 1, name='user_bias')(u_select)
    
    i_select = Lambda(lambda x: x[:, 1] - 1, name='item_selector')(inp)
    i_emb = Embedding(item_count, property_count, name='items')(i_select)
    i_emb_bias = Embedding(item_count, 1, name='item_bias')(i_select)
    
    tens = Multiply()([u_emb, i_emb])
    tens = Dropout(.5)(tens)
    tens = Concatenate()([tens, u_emb_bias, i_emb_bias])
    tens = Dense(15, activation='relu')(tens)
    tens = Dense(1)(tens)
    
    m = Model(inputs=inp, outputs=tens)
    m.compile(loss='mse', optimizer='adam', metrics=['mae'])
    return m

Interpreting the embeddings obtained is difficult, because they are composed of many dimensions.

Principal Component Analysis is a technique that can be used to lower the dimensionality of data. It isolates the axes along which the data communicates the most information.

In our case, the first principal component (X-axis of the scatter plot) seems to encode whether a book is a difficult read or not. "Twilight" is located diametrically opposed to "The Catcher in Rye", "1984" and the "Great Gatsby". The "Harry Potter" series is clustered together and is close to the "Hunger Games" series, which is to be expected, because people are often fans of both series.

    maxlen=40
    if len(s) > maxlen:
        return f'{s[:maxlen-3]}...'
    else:
        return s
